@node "Command Relabel" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

'Relabel' command:
=================

This command will work only under version 2.0 or later of the
operating system.  When selected, <Relabel> allows you to
rename a floppy disk, hard drive partion, or any other "volume".

To use the <Relabel> command, ensure that the @{"Volumes In Memory" link "Volumes In Memory"}
cycle gadget is displaying <Volumes in Memory> (rather than
<Devices, Assigns and Drives>).  Then, in the @{"List Area" link "List Area"}, select
the volume which you'd like to relabel.  Finally, select the
<Relabel> gadget.  A window similar to the following appears:

	 -------------------------------------
	|              Volume Name            |
	|                Empty:               |
	|                                     |
	|        Enter the new name to        |
	|        relabel this volume to       |
	|                                     |
	|   -------------------------------   |
	|  |                               |  |
	|   -------------------------------   |
	|   -----     ------       --------   |
	|  | Use |   | Skip |     | Cancel |  |
	|   -----     ------       --------   |
	 -------------------------------------

Enter the new volume name, and select the <Use> gadget.


See Also:   -

@endnode

@node "Command Rename" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

'Rename' command:
================

This command allows you to change any file(s) or directory(s)
to a new name.

To use, select any file(s) or directory(s) whose name you'd
like to change, and then select the <Rename> gadget.  A window
similar to the following appears:

	 -------------------------------------
	|           Source Directory          |
	|                 Work:               |
	|            Source Filename          |
	|                OldFile              |
	|         Destination Directory       |
	|                 Work:               |
	|                                     |
	|            Enter filename           |
	|        to rename this file to       |
	|                                     |
	|   -------------------------------   |
	|  |                               |  |
	|   -------------------------------   |
	|   -----     ------       --------   |
	|  | Use |   | Skip |     | Cancel |  |
	|   -----     ------       --------   |
	 -------------------------------------

Enter the new file or directory name, and select the <Use>
gadget.


See Also:   -

@endnode

@node "Command Reset All" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

'Reset All' command:
===================

This command forces MegaD to redraw all currently open directory
windows.  This is useful after you've modified the sort or display
attributes of the directory windows.

As an example, open two or more directory windows.  After having
opened them, change one of the @{"Show menu" link "Menu Show"} items.  For instance, if
the menu item @{"Show" link "Menu Show"} / @{"Size" link "Menu Show - Size"} was turned off, then turn it on.  Notice
how only the currently selected directory window will show file
sizes.  To force all currently open directory windows to show
filesize, select the menu item <Show / Reset All>.


See Also:   -

@endnode

@node "Command Save As..." "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

'Save As...' command  &  @{" Menu Project " link "Menu Project"} / 'Save As...' menu item:
================================================================

This command allows you to save the current MegaD preferences
under a filename of your choosing.  

MegaD uses the file "megad2.pf" as the default preference file.
If you want to save more than one preference file, then use the
<Save As> option.  Later, when you want to reuse that preference
file, you can use the @{"Open..." link "Command Open..."} command.


See Also:   @{" Open...          " link "Command Open..."} built-in command
            @{" Save Preferences " link "Command Save Preferences"} built-in command
            @{" Project " link "Menu Project"} / @{" Open...          " link "Command Open..."} menu item
            @{" Project " link "Menu Project"} / @{" Save Preferences " link "Command Save Preferences"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Command Save Preferences" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

'Save Preferences' command  &  @{" Menu Project " link "Menu Project"} / 'Save Preferences' menu item:
============================================================================

The <Save Preferences> command saves the current MegaD preferences
as "megad2.pf", or as the last @{"Save As..." link "Command Save As..."} filename.


