@node "Program Control - Query For Flags To Add" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

Query for 'Flags to Add' (@{" program control window - page 2 " link "Program Control Window 2"}):
============================================================

The <Query for 'Flags to Add'> gadget is similar to the
@{"Flags to add after Program Name" link "Program Control - Flags To Add After Program Name"} gadget on page 1 of the program
control window.  If you select the <Query for 'Flags to Add'>
gadget, then prior to launching the program, MegaD will query you
for any flags to add immediately following the program name in
the command line.

There's only one difference between <Query for 'Flags to Add'> and
@{"Flags to add after Program Name" link "Program Control - Flags To Add After Program Name"}.  <Query for 'Flags to Add'> gives
the user the ability to decide which flags to use AT THE TIME OF
PROGRAM EXECUTION, rather than at the time the program control is
created.

For information on how MegaD builds a command line, refer to
@{"Command Lines And Program Control" link "Command Lines And Program Control"}.



See Also:   @{" Program Control - Page 1          " link "Program Control Window 1"} window
            @{" Program Control - Page 2          " link "Program Control Window 2"} window
            @{" Command Lines And Program Control " link "Command Lines And Program Control"} discussion

@endnode

@node "Program Control - Query For Text To Append" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

Query for 'Text to append' (@{" program control window - page 2 " link "Program Control Window 2"}):
==============================================================

The <Query for 'Text to append'> gadget is similar to the
@{"Text to append to end of Command Line" link "Program Control - Text To Append To End Of Command Line"} gadget located on the
1st page of the program control window.  If you select the
<Query for 'Text to append'> gadget, then prior to launching
the program, MegaD will query you for any text you'd like
added to the end of the command line.

There's only one difference between the two.  <Query for
'Text to append'> gives the user the ability to decide which
text to use AT THE TIME OF PROGRAM EXECUTION, rather than at
the time the program control is created.

For information on how MegaD builds a command line, refer to
@{"Command Lines And Program Control" link "Command Lines And Program Control"}.



See Also:   @{" Program Control - Page 1          " link "Program Control Window 1"} window
            @{" Program Control - Page 2          " link "Program Control Window 2"} window
            @{" Command Lines And Program Control " link "Command Lines And Program Control"} discussion

@endnode

@node "Program Control - Console Window String" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

Console window string (@{" program control window - page 2 " link "Program Control Window 2"}):
=========================================================

Whenever MegaD launches a program as a @{"CLI process" link "Program Control - Execute Type Cycle Gadget"}, it automatically
opens a console window.  This string gadget allows you to specify the
location and dimensions of this console window.  If you leave this
string gadget blank,  MegaD automatically chooses a default location
and size for the console window.  If, on the other hand, you want to
set the size and location of this window, use the following format
for a string:

     CON:10/22/150/200

     CON - Means console window.
     10  - Window left edge (in pixels).
     22  - Window top edge (in pixels).
     150 - Window width (in pixels).
     200 - Window height (in pixels).

There's actually an easier way to define the location and size of the
console window.  Immediately to the right of the <Console window string>
gadget, you should see a @{"gadget resembling a window's 'close gadget'" link "Program Control - Close Sizing Gadget"}.

If you single-click on this @{"'close gadget'" link "Program Control - Close Sizing Gadget"}, then a new window appears
on the screen.  The window is titled, "Adjust window to proper size,
then close".  Do just that...size and place that window to the exact
location and dimensions that you'd like the console window to be, then
close the window. Once you close the window, a string defining that
window's dimensions will appear in the <Console window string> gadget.


See Also:   @{" Program Control - Page 1 " link "Program Control Window 1"} window
            @{" Program Control - Page 2 " link "Program Control Window 2"} window

@endnode

@node "Program Control - Close Sizing Gadget" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

close sizing gadget (@{" program control window - page 2 " link "Program Control Window 2"}):
=======================================================

Whenever MegaD launches a program as a @{"CLI process" link "Program Control - Execute Type Cycle Gadget"}, it automatically
opens a console window.  This "close window" sizing gadget allows you
to define the location and dimensions of this console window.

If you single-click on this "close" gadget, then a new window appears
on the screen.  The window is titled, "Adjust window to proper size,
then close".  Do just that...size and place that window to the exact
location and dimensions that you'd like the console window to be, then
close the window. Once you close the window, a string defining that
window's dimensions will appear in the @{"Console window string" link "Program Control - Console Window String"} gadget.


See Also:   @{" Program Control - Page 1 " link "Program Control Window 1"} window
            @{" Program Control - Page 2 " link "Program Control Window 2"} window

@endnode

@node "Program Control - Stack Size" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

Stack Size (@{" program control window - page 2 " link "Program Control Window 2"}):
==============================================

This gadget, as you might suspect, allows you to alter the size of
the stack allocated for this program.  When MegaD launches a program,
it uses the following priority to determine stack size:

1.  Stack size set in @{"page 2 of the program control window" link "Program Control Window 2"}.

2.  If the user doesn't enter a stack size in the program control
    window, then MegaD uses the stack size specified in the launched
    program's associated icon.  (MegaD will use this method even if
    the program was launched as a @{"CLI process" link "Program Control - Execute Type Cycle Gadget"}).

3.  If the program doesn't have an associated icon, MegaD uses
    it's own stack size - that is, whatever you have set for MegaD's
    stack, will be set for the newly launched program.

4.  MegaD will ensure that the stack size is at least 4096 bytes.



See Also:   @{" Program Control - Page 1 " link "Program Control Window 1"} window
            @{" Program Control - Page 2 " link "Program Control Window 2"} window

@endnode

@node "Command Lines And Program Control" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

Command Lines and Program Controls (@{" program control window - page 1 " link "Program Control Window 1"}):
======================================================================

Now I'd like to warn those of you who are not too CLI knowledgable,
or who are faint of heart, that the following won't be easy...On the
other hand, a basic understanding of this is necessary to configuring
MegaD.

When working with AmigaDOS and CLI command lines, MegaD must create
full sentences (command lines) in order to tell the called program
exactly what the user wants done.  MegaD uses all of the information
in the program control string gadgets.  Additionally, it uses information
from files selected within directory windows.  To form a command line,
MegaD pieces all of this information together in the following order:

   @{" Path and Program Name " link "Program Control - Path and Program Name"}
   > @{" Redirect Output to a file or device " link "Program Control - Redirect Output To A File Or Device"}
   < @{" Accept Input From a file or device " link "Program Control - Accept Input From A File Or Device"}
   @{" Flags to add after Program Name " link "Program Control - Flags To Add After Program Name"} -or- @{" Query for 'Flags to add' " link "Program Control - Query For Flags To Add"}
   @{" Query for destination filename " link "Program Control - Query For Destination Filename"}
   complete filenames of selected files
   @{" Text to append to end of Command Line " link "Program Control - Text To Append To End Of Command Line"} -or- @{" Query for 'Text to append' " link "Program Control - Query For Text To Append"}

I'm going to attempt to "diagram" a complete CLI command in the same
manner in which MegaD would create it:


@{" Path and Program Name " link "Program Control - Path and Program Name"}
       |
       |    @{" Accept Input From a file or device " link "Program Control - Accept Input From A File Or Device"}
       |                     |
       |                     |         @{" Flags to add after Program Name " link "Program Control - Flags To Add After Program Name"} 
       |                     |    ----             -or- 
       |                     |    |    @{" Query for 'Flags to add' " link "Program Control - Query For Flags To Add"}
       |                     |    | 
       |                     |    | 
       |                     |    | 
       V                     V    V 
Work:Crunchers/LhA  >NIL:  <NIL:  e  Work:Archives/MegaD.LhA  Ram:
                      ^                 ^                      ^
                      |                 |                      |
                      |                 |                      |
                      |                 |                      |
                      |                 |   @{" Query for destination filename " link "Program Control - Query For Destination Filename"}
                      |                 |                    -or-
                      |                 |   @{" Text to append to end of Command Line " link "Program Control - Text To Append To End Of Command Line"}
                      |                 |                    -or-
                      |                 |   @{" Query for 'Text to append' " link "Program Control - Query For Text To Append"}
                      |                 |
                      |     This represents the file(s)
                      | selected within directory window(s)
                      |
     @{" Redirect Output to a file or device " link "Program Control - Redirect Output To A File Or Device"}


 ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| @{"  " link "Program Control - Skip Selected Directories"} * Skip selected directories        Title     @{" Verify Title & Path/name " link "Program Control - Verify Title & Pathname"}   |
| @{"  " link "Program Control - Skip Selected Files"} * Skip selected files              @{" LhA Unpack                         " link "Program Control - Title"}   |
| @{"  " link "Program Control - Work Without Selected Items"} * Work without selected items      Path and Program name                  |
| @{"  " link "Program Control - Skip .Info Files"} * Skip .info files                 @{" Work:Crunchers/LhA              " link "Program Control - Path And Program Name"} @{"  " link "Program Control - Getfile Gadget"}   |
| @{"  " link "Program Control - Combine All Selected On One Line"} * Combine all selected on one line Flags to add after Program Name        |
| @{"  " link "Program Control - Workbench Screen To Front At Start"} Workbench screen to front at start @{" e                                  " link "Program Control - Flags To Add After Program Name"}   |
| @{"  " link "Program Control - MegaD Screen To Front At End"} MegaD screen to front at end       Text to append to end of Command Line  |
| @{"  " link "Program Control - Reload Current Directory At End"} * Reload current directory at end  @{" Ram:                               " link "Program Control - Text To Append To End of Command Line"}   |
| @{"  " link "Program Control - Query For Destination Filename"} * Query for destination filename   Redirect Output to a file or device    |
| @{"  " link "Program Control - Warn Before Launch"} Warn before launch                 @{" NIL:                               " link "Program Control - Redirect Output To A File Or Device"}   |
| @{"@   Place Program on MegaD Screen  " link "Program Control - Screen Control Cycle Gadget"}   Accept Input from a file or device     |
| @{"@                 CLI              " link "Program Control - Execute Type Cycle Gadget"}   @{" NIL:                               " link "Program Control - Accept Input From A File Or Device"}   |
|         @{"      More...     " link "Program Control Window 2"} | @{"       Use       " link "Main"}  @{"      Cancel       " link "Main"}          |
 ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The is program control reflect the command line listed above 
(we are only concerned with the right side of the program control
window here - you'd still need to fill out the left side):

Sorry you had to experience all that, but the formation of a command
line is fairly complex, and I had to supply this information somewhere.



See Also:   @{" Program Control - Page 1 " link "Program Control Window 1"} window
            @{" Program Control - Page 2 " link "Program Control Window 2"} window

@endnode

