@node "Flags From ARexx" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"


        Other Flags Set from ARexx:
        ==========================
		
        When adding features to MegaD and ways to customize the way the
        program works from one user to the next, one of the biggest
        overhead is creating a way for the user to set those settings.
        With the release of 3.1 I have decided to try a slightly
        deferent approach.  All of the internal preference settings of
        MegaD can be changed from ARexx with very simple ARexx programs.
        The following settings can only be set from ARexx  and each
        example is fully functional and commented:

        ----------------------------- Cut ----------------------------
        /*
        MegaD has the ability to launch ARexx programs.  This can be
        done in a number of ways.  This program will let you set the
        action MegaD performs when you double click and ARexx program
        from a Directory Window.
        */

        ADDRESS MEGAD
		
        /*
        Tell MegaD to only View ARexx programs when an ARexx script is
        double clicked.
        */

        SetFlag 123 1 

        /*
        The '123' of the above command tells MegaD which flag to
        changed.  The '1' is the value that the flag to be changed to.
        This flag can be set to the following values.
        '0'    Launch or View ARexx scripts when double clicked
        '1'    Always view ARexx scripts when double clicked
        '2'    Always launch ARexx scripts when double clicked
        */
        ----------------------------- Cut ----------------------------
        /*
        MegaD will warn you if you are attempting to load a text file
        into a Text Window.  You can turn it off by using this ARexx
        program.
        */

        ADDRESS MEGAD

        /*
        Turn off warnings before loading HEX files into View Text
        Windows.
        */

        SetFlag 124 1

        /* 
        The '124' of the above command tells MegaD which flag to
        changed.  The '1' is the value that the flag to be changed to.
        This flag can be set to the following values.
        '0'    Warn before loading a HEX file into a Text Window
        '1'    No Waring before loading a HEX file into a Text Window
        */
        ----------------------------- Cut ----------------------------



@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Auto Resize Windows" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"
@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Auto Resize Windows:
======================================

When you select <Auto Resize Windows> (assuming you have also
selected the menu item @{"Windows" link "Menu Windows"} / @{"Use Overlap Locations" link "Menu Windows - Use Overlap Locations"}, then
MegaD will automatically size @{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"} to the exact
size needed to display all information.  In other words, the
@{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"} will display all files and directories,
without using excess space.


See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Auto Update Windows" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Auto Update Windows:
======================================

If you select <Auto Update Windows>, then MegaD will re-read the
contents of a directory every time its @{"directory window" link "Directory Windows"} is opened.

Refer to @{"buffered directories" link "Buffered Directories"} for further explanation.


See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Confirm Quit" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Confirm Quit:
===============================

If you select <Confirm Quit>, then anytime you attempt to quit
MegaD, the following requester will verify that you REALLY do
want to quit.

             ----------------
            |   Quit  MegaD  |
            |  -----   ----  |
            | | Yes | | No | |
            |  -----   ----  |
             ----------------



See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window
            @{" Quit     " link "Command Quit"} built-in command
            @{" Project " link "Menu Project"} / @{" Quit " link "Command Quit"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Display Memory, Date, Time" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Display Memory, Date, Time:
=============================================

If you select <Display memory, date, time>, then MegaD will intermittantly
display the following information in the screen's title bar:

   C: 610,304  F: 1,140,304  L: 752,376  T: 1,750,608  06-02-93 19:37:46

   Where C = amount of chip memory available
         F = amount of fast memory available
         L = largest continuous chunk of memory available
         T = total amount of memory available (chip & fast)

This information will be intermittantly displayed, and will only be
displayed when a MegaD window is active.
   


See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Display File, Directories, Bytes" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Display File, Directories, Bytes:
===================================================

If you select <Display file, directories, bytes>, MegaD will intermittantly
display the following information in the screen's title bar:

   Files: 5   Dirs: 2   Bytes: 1,547,329   FSpace: 14,371,259

   Where:   Files  =  total files selected  -or-  source files selected
            Dirs   =  total dirs  selected  -or-  source dirs selected
            Bytes  =  total bytes selected  -or-  source bytes selected
            FSpace =  free space available on destination volume

This information will be intermittantly displayed, and it will only be
displayed when a MegaD window is active.

Refer to the section covering @{"MegaD's main window files selected area" link "Files Selected Area"}
for a more indepth discussion of this subject.



See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Iconify At Start" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Iconify At Start:
===================================

If you select <Iconify at start>, then when MegaD is run, it will
automatically @{"iconify" link "Command Iconify"} itself into an @{"application icon" link "Application Icons"}.



See Also:   @{" Defaults          " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window
            @{" Iconify           " link "Command Iconify"} built-in command
            @{" Project " link "Menu Project"} / @{" Iconify " link "Command Iconify"} menu item
            @{" Application Icons " link "Application Icons"} discussion

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Keep Active Window To Front" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Keep Active Window To Front:
==============================================

If you select <Keep active window to front>, then MegaD will
automatically move any newly selected @{"directory window" link "Directory Windows"} or
text window to the front of the screen.

I want to draw a distinction between the active window and a
destination window:

   A destination window is any directory window (possibly more
   than 1) whose @{"DEST" link "DEST Gadget"} gadget is selected.  Destination windows
   have nothing to do with the <Keep active window to front>
   gadget.
   
   An active window is THE directory window (only 1) in which
   the mouse was last clicked.  You can recognize it by the
   fact that its border is a different color from all non-active
   windows on the screen.  The <Keep active window to front>
   preference deals with this window.

This will have no affect on moving MegaD's main window to the
front.



See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Last Active Window Is Destination" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Last Active Window Is Destination:
====================================================

This preference is a bit difficult to put into words, so I'll
attempt to explain it using an example.


1. <Last active window is destination> selected:
   ============================================
   
   To start this example, lets say you don't have any directory windows
   open on your screen.
   
   - You open a @{"directory window" link "Directory Windows"} for your <Work:> directory.  The
     Amiga automatically makes this @{"directory window" link "Directory Windows"} the screen's
     active window (as is evident by its colored border).
     
     This directory IS NOT the @{"DEST" link "DEST Gadget"} window (because it wasn't the
     last active window - on the contrary, it is the current active
     window).
     
   - You open a new @{"directory window" link "Directory Windows"} for your <Ram:> directory. The
     Amiga automatically makes the <Ram:> @{"directory window" link "Directory Windows"} the
     screen's active window (<Work:> is no longer the screen's active
     window).
     
     At this time, <Ram:> (the currently active window) is a source
     window, and <Work:> (the "last" active window) is the @{"DEST" link "DEST Gadget"}
     window.
   
   - Clear as mud???
   
   Why would you want a setup like this?  If you choose to work with
   only two @{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"} open on the screen, this setup would
   be convenient.  Operations such as copying a file would be simple
   because, the moment you select the file to copy, the other directory
   becomes the destination.
   
   
2. <Last active window is destination> IS NOT SELECTED:
   ===================================================

   This one's easy to explain.  Whichever @{"directory window" link "Directory Windows"} is the
   screen's active window, is also the @{"DEST" link "DEST Gadget"} window.
   
   If you plan on running MegaD with 3 or more @{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"}
   open at once, I'd suggest running in this mode.



See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Place Tool Icon & Menu On Workbench" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Place Tool Icon & Menu On Workbench:
======================================================

If you select the <Place tool icon & menu on workbench>, MegaD will,
upon startup, place an @{"appicon" link "Application Icons"} on the Workbench screen.  It will
also place two menu items in your Workbench Utilities menu:

   Call MegaD
   Quit MegaD



NOTE: This preference will not take place until you have
      
         (1) Saved the preference, and
         (2) Restarted MegaD.
      
      Don't be confused if you save this preference and don't
      see an immediate @{"appicon" link "Application Icons"} or menu items.  They won't appear
      until the next time you start up MegaD.
      


See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Messages Off" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Messages Off:
===============================

Many MegaD functions will generate information only messages.
You can generally recognize these messages because the only
gadget they contain is a <Continue> gadget.

If you select <Messages Off>, then MegaD will suppress these
informational messages.

NOTE:  The information in these messages usually explains why
       a task or function failed to work properly.  If you
       select <Messages Off>, you may be asking for confusion,
       since a failed process won't explain itself for you.



See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Panic Button Window" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Panic Button Window:
======================================

It's probably safe to say the we've all experienced that sinking
panic...you know right after you depress the return key to delete
a directory.  For a split second, you're afraid that you might be
deleting the wrong directory.

MegaD provides a method to minimize damage when you get this
sick-to-your-stomach feeling.  It's called the panic window.

If you select the <Panic button window> in @{"default preferences" link "Prefs Defaults"},
then whenever you initiate a delete, copy, move... operation,
MegaD opens a window called the panic window.  The panic window
looks like the following:


    ------------------------------------------------------
   |                                                      |
   |                                                      |
   |                                                      |
   |                                                      |
   |                                                      |
   |                                                      |
   | Deleting File DpaintIV.info                          |
   | Deleting File Excellence!.info                       |
   | Deleting File Games.info                             |
   |------------------------------------------------------|
   | @{" Suspend " link "Panic Window - Suspend"}                                  @{" Cancel " link "Panic Window - Cancel"}  |
    ------------------------------------------------------


What the panic window allows is for you to immediately "suspend"
or "cancel" the current operation, thereby minimizing damage.

NOTE:  Whatever actions have occurred prior to suspending or
       cancelling the operation, are done...forever.  The panic
       window will not allow "undoing" an operation.  It merely
       prevents the damage from being to great.



See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window
            @{" Panic " link "Menu Panic"} / @{" STOP PROCESS " link "Menu Panic - STOP PROCESS"} menu item
            @{" Panic " link "Menu Panic"} / @{" CANCEL PRINT " link "Menu Panic - CANCEL PRINT"} menu item
            @{" Panic " link "Menu Panic"} / @{" CANCEL ALL PRINT " link "Menu Panic - CANCEL ALL PRINT"} menu item
            @{" Cancel   " link "Panic Window - Cancel"} panic window button
            @{" Suspend  " link "Panic Window - Suspend"} panic window button

@endnode

@node "Panic Window - Suspend" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

 Panic Window  - 'Suspend' gadget:
=================================

When you select the <Suspend> gadget, MegaD temporarily stops whatever
operation it is currently performing.  You will be able to recognize
the temporary suspension of the process because the <Suspend> gadget
will be higlighted.  Additionally, any text scrolling through the
panic window will stop.

At that point, you have one of two options:

(1)  Continue the process by deselecting the <Suspend> gadget.

(2)  Terminate the process by selecting the @{"panic window's Cancel" link "Panic Window - Cancel"}
     gadget.



See Also:   @{" Defaults            " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window
            @{" Panic " link "Menu Panic"} / @{" STOP PROCESS " link "Menu Panic - STOP PROCESS"} menu item
            @{" Panic " link "Menu Panic"} / @{" CANCEL PRINT " link "Menu Panic - CANCEL PRINT"} menu item
            @{" Panic " link "Menu Panic"} / @{" CANCEL ALL PRINT " link "Menu Panic - CANCEL ALL PRINT"} menu item
            @{" Panic Button Window " link "Prefs Defaults - Panic Button Window"} defaults preference
            @{" Cancel              " link "Panic Window - Cancel"} panic window button

@endnode

@node "Panic Window - Cancel" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

 Panic Window  - 'Cancel' gadget:
================================

When you select the panic window's <Cancel> gadget, MegaD opens the
following window:

    ---------------------------
   |   Are you sure that you   |
   | want to cancel this task? |
   |  -----              ----  |
   | | Yes |            | No | |
   |  -----              ----  |
    ---------------------------

If you answer <Yes> at this point, then MegaD completely stops the
current operation, however, MegaD will not "undo" any actions that
have already been accomplished.  NOTE: Yoy cab determine what
actions MegaD has already accomplished by reading the text inside
the @{"panic window" link "Prefs Defaults - Panic Button Window"}

If you answer <No> to this requeser, then MegaD will continue with
the process.



See Also:   @{" Defaults            " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window
            @{" Panic " link "Menu Panic"} / @{" STOP PROCESS " link "Menu Panic - STOP PROCESS"} menu item
            @{" Panic " link "Menu Panic"} / @{" CANCEL PRINT " link "Menu Panic - CANCEL PRINT"} menu item
            @{" Panic " link "Menu Panic"} / @{" CANCEL ALL PRINT " link "Menu Panic - CANCEL ALL PRINT"} menu item
            @{" Panic Button Window " link "Prefs Defaults - Panic Button Window"} defaults preference
            @{" Suspend             " link "Panic Window - Suspend"} panic window button

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Return Keypad To Unshifted" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Return Keypad To Unshifted:
=============================================

MegaD offers two ways of selecting the <Ctrl>, <Shift> and <Alt>
@{"numeric keypads" link "Numeric Keypad Gadgets"}.  You can hold down the appropriate key on the
keyboard, or you can select the @{" C " link "Ctrl & Shift & Alt Gadgets"}, @{" S " link "Ctrl & Shift & Alt Gadgets"} or @{" A " link "Ctrl & Shift & Alt Gadgets"} gadgets in MegaD's
@{"main window" link "MegaD Main Window"}.

The <Return keypad to unshifted> preference deals solely with the
times you use the mouse to select the @{" C " link "Ctrl & Shift & Alt Gadgets"}, @{" S " link "Ctrl & Shift & Alt Gadgets"} or @{" A " link "Ctrl & Shift & Alt Gadgets"} gadget.


<Return keypad to unshifted> selected:
=====================================

   Lets say that you use the mouse to select the @{" C " link "Ctrl & Shift & Alt Gadgets"} bank of numeric
   @{"keypad" link "Numeric Keypad Gadgets"} gadgets, and then you execute a command on one of the keypad
   gadgets.
   
   As soon as the command is finished, the MegaD main window will
   automatically return from the @{" C " link "Ctrl & Shift & Alt Gadgets"} bank to the original bank of
   gadgets.


<Return keypad to unshifted> NOT SELECTED:
=========================================

   Again, lets say you use the mouse to select the @{" C " link "Ctrl & Shift & Alt Gadgets"} bank of numeric
   @{"keypad" link "Numeric Keypad Gadgets"} gadgets, and then you execute a command on one of the keypad
   gadgets.
   
   The MegaD main window will remain on the @{" C " link "Ctrl & Shift & Alt Gadgets"} bank of @{"numeric keypad" link "Numeric Keypad Gadgets"}
   gadgets after the command is finished.



See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Save Defaults At Closing" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Save Defaults At Closing:
===========================================

If you select <Save defaults at closing>, MegaD will automatically
save the current preference settings prior to quitting.


See Also:   @{" Defaults         " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window
            @{" Save Preferences " link "Command Save Preferences"} built-in command
            @{" Menu Project " link "Menu Project"} / @{" Save Preferences " link "Command Save Preferences"}

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Save Window Positions" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Save Window Positions:
========================================

If you select <Save Window Positions>, then MegaD will remember the
locations of requesters.  Each time MegaD needs to open that requester,
it will do so in the position it last remembered.

If you choose not to select this preference, then MegaD attempts to
open requesters directly under the current mouse position.


See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Simple Refresh Windows" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Simple Refresh Windows:
=========================================

For folks tight on memory, selecting the <Simple refresh windows>
preference can help.

When you use simple refresh windows, you save memory at the expense
of slower refresh rates when moving, sizing, and uncovering windows.


See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Warn Before Copy" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Warn Before Copy:
===================================

When <Warn before copy> is selected, a requester similar to the
following opens before any copy operation is commenced:


      ---------------------------------------
     |        5 File/s marked for copy       |
     |   0 Directory/ies  marked for copy    |
     | To be copied to 1 directory window/s  |
     |               Continue                |
     |---------------------------------------|
     |   -----                        ----   |
     |  | Yes |                      | No |  |
     |   -----                        ----   |
      ---------------------------------------


See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window
            @{" Copy     " link "Command Copy"} built-in command
            @{" Copy As  " link "Command Copy As"} built-in command

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Warn Before Delete" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Warn Before Delete:
=====================================

When <Warn before delete> is selected, a requester similar to the
following opens before any delete operation is commenced:


           -------------------------------------
          |      2 File/s marked for delete     |
          |  1 Directory/ies marked for delete  |
          |              Continue               |
          |-------------------------------------|
          |   -------                  ------   |
          |  |  Yes  |                |  No  |  |
          |   -------                  ------   |
           -------------------------------------

Additionally, if you happen to have files/directories selected in
more than one directory window, MegaD will open an unmistakable
requester similar to the following:

      ----------------------------------------------
     |          2 File/s marked for delete          |
     |      1 Directory/ies marked for delete       |
     | <<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>> |
     |   <<< In 2 different directory windows >>>   |
     | <<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>> |
     |                   Continue                   |
     |----------------------------------------------|
     |   -------                           ------   |
     |  |  Yes  |                         |  No  |  |
     |   -------                           ------   |
      ----------------------------------------------

The purpose behind this second requester is to "catch your eye".
Every now and then you will have selected files in multiple
directories - thinking that you only have files in 1 directory
selected.  If you attempt to delete files in this situation,
this "catchy" will make you think before you delete!


See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window
            @{" Delete   " link "Command Delete"} built-in command

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Warn Before Move" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Warn Before Move:
===================================

When <Warn before move> is selected, a requester similar to the
following opens before any move operation is commenced:


      ---------------------------------------
     |        1 File/s marked for move       |
     |    0 Directory/ies marked for move    |
     |  To be moved to 2 directory window/s  |
     |               Continue                |
     |---------------------------------------|
     |   -----                        ----   |
     |  | Yes |                      | No |  |
     |   -----                        ----   |
      ---------------------------------------


See Also:   @{" Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window
            @{" Move     " link "Command Move"} built-in command
            @{" Move As  " link "Command Move As"} built-in command

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Warn If Deleting Protected File" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Warn If Deleting Protected File:
==================================================

When <Warn if deleting protected file> is selected, a requester
similar to the following opens for every write protected file
that MegaD attempts to delete:


       -----------------
      |   File MyFile   |
      |   is protected  |
      |  Delete Anyway  |
      |-----------------|
      |  -----    ----  |
      | | Yes |  | No | |
      |  -----    ----  |
       -----------------


See Also:   @{" Defaults    " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window
            @{" Delete      " link "Command Delete"} built-in command
            @{" Set Protect " link "Command Set Protect"} built-in command
            @{" Show " link "Menu Show"} / @{" Show Protection " link "Menu Show - Protection"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Warn If Replacing Larger File" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Warn If Replacing Larger File:
================================================

When <Warn if replacing larger file> is selected, a requester
similar to the following opens whenever you attempt to replace
a file with a larger one:


       -----------------------
      | You will be replacing |
      |    the larger file    |
      |       MyBigFile       |
      |     in  directory     |
      |         Ram:          |
      |      Replace it?      |
      |-----------------------|
      |  -----          ----  |
      | | Yes |        | No | |
      |  -----          ----  |
       -----------------------


See Also:   @{" Defaults    " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Warn If Replacing Newer File" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Warn If Replacing Newer File:
===============================================

When <Warn if replacing newer file> is selected, a requester
similar to the following opens whenever you attempt to replace
a newer file with an older one:


       -----------------------
      | You will be replacing |
      |    the  newer file    |
      |       MyNewFile       |
      |     in  directory     |
      |         Ram:          |
      |      Replace it?      |
      |-----------------------|
      |  -----          ----  |
      | | Yes |        | No | |
      |  -----          ----  |
       -----------------------


See Also:   @{" Defaults    " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Warn If Replacing File" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Warn If Replacing File:
=========================================


When <Warn if replacing file> is selected, a requester
similar to the following opens whenever you attempt to
replace any file with another:


       -----------------------
      | You will be replacing |
      |        AnyFile        |
      |     in directory      |
      |         Ram:          |
      |      Replace it?      |
      |-----------------------|
      |  -----          ----  |
      | | Yes |        | No | |
      |  -----          ----  |
       -----------------------


See Also:   @{" Defaults    " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - Warn If Replacing Preference File" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - Warn If Replacing Preference File:
====================================================

When you select the <Warn if replacing preference file> option,
a requester similar to the following will appear if you attempt
to replace a preference file using MegaD's  @{"Save Preferences" link "Command Save Preferences"},
or @{"Save As..." link "Command Save As..."} commands:


       -----------------------
      | You will be replacing |
      |       MegaD2.pf       |
      |        Continue       |
      |-----------------------|
      |  -----          ----  |
      | | Yes |        | No | |
      |  -----          ----  |
       -----------------------


See Also:   @{" Defaults         " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window
            @{" Save As...       " link "Command Save As..."} built-in command
            @{" Save Preferences " link "Command Save Preferences"} built-in command

@endnode

@node "Prefs Defaults - F10 Closes Control Window" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Prefs Defaults " link "Prefs Defaults"} - F10 Closes Control Window:
============================================

The F10 key can function in two manners, depending upon the status
of this preference:


   <F10 closes control window> selected:
   ====================================
   
      Many (if not most) of MegaD's commands can be initiated from the
      keyboard.  For that reason, MegaD's @{"main window" link "MegaD Main Window"} is not really a
      necessity (provided at least one @{"directory window" link "Directory Windows"} is already open).
      
      Assuming AT LEAST 1 @{"directory window" link "Directory Windows"} is open, pressing the F10 key,
      closes the MegaD @{"main window" link "MegaD Main Window"}.  It will not close any open
      @{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"}.  Additionally, it will NOT create a MegaD
      appicon.
      
      At this point, you must either use the keyboard to execute MegaD
      commands, or you must select the F10 key again (to get the window
      back).
      
      (NEW 2.x)   This attribute also works with @{"gadget sets" link "Gadget Sets"}.  If you
                  define any @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"} with the @{"Open At Startup" link "Gadget Set - Open At Startup"} pref,
                  and this item is checked, then MegaD will open the
                  @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"} instead of the @{"main control window" link "MegaD Main Window"}.


   
   
   <F10 closes control window> NOT SELECTED:
   ========================================
   
      Under this configuration, depressing the F10 key will move MegaD's
      @{"main window" link "MegaD Main Window"} to the back of the screen.  Pressing it a second time
      will return the MegaD window to the front of the screen.



See Also:   @{" Defaults         " link "Prefs Defaults"} preference window

@endnode

