@node "Gadget Set - Close Once Used" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Gadget Set Window " link "Gadget Set Window"} - Close Once Used:
=====================================

If you select the <Close once used> gadget, the @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"} will
automatically close once you make your first selection from it.

If you do not select <Close once used>, then you will have to
manually close the @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"} when you no longer want to use it.


See Also:   @{" Gadget Set            " link "Gadget Set Window"} definition window
            @{" Keypads - Gadget Sets " link "Prefs Keypads - Gadget Sets"} preference window
            @{" Gadget Sets           " link "Gadget Sets"} discussion

@endnode

@node "Gadget Set - Keep To Front" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Gadget Set Window " link "Gadget Set Window"} - Keep To Front:
===================================

If you select the <Keep to Front> preference, then MegaD will
ensure that the @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"} remains in front of other windows.


See Also:   @{" Gadget Set            " link "Gadget Set Window"} definition window
            @{" Keypads - Gadget Sets " link "Prefs Keypads - Gadget Sets"} preference window
            @{" Gadget Sets           " link "Gadget Sets"} discussion

@endnode

@node "Gadget Set - Open At Startup" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Gadget Set Window " link "Gadget Set Window"} - Open At Startup:
=====================================

If you select the <Open at startup> gadget, then the @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"}
will automatically open upon MegaD startup.


See Also:   @{" Gadget Set            " link "Gadget Set Window"} definition window
            @{" Keypads - Gadget Sets " link "Prefs Keypads - Gadget Sets"} preference window
            @{" Gadget Sets           " link "Gadget Sets"} discussion

@endnode

@node "Gadget Set - Window Type" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Gadget Set Window " link "Gadget Set Window"} - Window Type:
=================================

The <Window Type> cycle gadget has three possibilities:

   Fixed:        - MegaD will remember its screen location, and
                   will reopen it at the same spot each time.
                 
                 - This @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"} window will have a drag bar.
                 
                 - The @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"} window has a close gadget.
   
   
   Rigid:        - MegaD will remember its screen location, and
                   will reopen it at the same spot each time.
                 
                 - This @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"} window will not have a drag
                   bar (under WB 2.0 or higher, this window can
                   be moved with the cursor keys while the Shift,
                   or the Ctrl-Shift keys are pressed).
                 
                 - The @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"} window does not have a close
                   gadget (but can be closed using the Esc key).
   
   
   Under Mouse:  MegaD will attempt to open the @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"} window
                 directly under the mouse pointer.
   

See Also:   @{" Gadget Set            " link "Gadget Set Window"} definition window
            @{" Keypads - Gadget Sets " link "Prefs Keypads - Gadget Sets"} preference window
            @{" Gadget Sets           " link "Gadget Sets"} discussion

@endnode

@node "Gadget Set - Close Sizing Gadget" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Gadget Set Window " link "Gadget Set Window"} - Close Sizing Gadget:
=========================================

The @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"} definition window contains a small gadget resembling
a window's "close gadget".  It is located between the @{"Window Type" link "Gadget Set - Window Type"}
cycle gadget and the @{"Duplicate" link "Gadget Set - Duplicate"} gadget.

When you select this <close window sizing> gadget, MegaD opens a
window labelled "Adjust window to proper size, then close".  What
it is asking you to do is to size the window to the dimensions you
would like the @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"} to be.  Once you've done that, close
the window.

At that point, MegaD will automatically place the dimensions of
that window into the @{"Inner Window Width" link "Gadget Set - Inner Window Width"} and the @{"Inner Window Height" link "Gadget Set - Inner Window Height"}
gadgets.

This method is generally much easier than manually entering values
for inner window width and height.


See Also:   @{" Gadget Set                       " link "Gadget Set Window"} definition window
            @{" Gadget Set - Inner Window Height " link "Gadget Set - Inner Window Height"} definition
            @{" Gadget Set - Inner Window Width  " link "Gadget Set - Inner Window Width"} definition
            @{" Keypads - Gadget Sets            " link "Prefs Keypads - Gadget Sets"} preference window
            @{" Gadget Sets                      " link "Gadget Sets"} discussion

@endnode

@node "Gadget Set - Duplicate" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Gadget Set Window " link "Gadget Set Window"} - Duplicate:
===============================

When you select the <Duplicate> gadget, MegaD will create an identical
@{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"}.  MegaD will give the new @{"gadget set" link "Gadget Sets"} the same name as the
original, except it will append a 1 to the end.


See Also:   @{" Gadget Set            " link "Gadget Set Window"} definition window
            @{" Keypads - Gadget Sets " link "Prefs Keypads - Gadget Sets"} preference window
            @{" Gadget Sets           " link "Gadget Sets"} discussion

@endnode

@node "Application Icons" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

Application Icons:
=================

Application Icons (appicons) and Application Windows (appwindows)
are only availible to folks running WorkBench 2.0 or higher. MegaD
uses application icons.  Additionally, MegaD's @{"main window" link "MegaD Main Window"} is an
application window.

When you "drag" another workbench icon (such as a drawer, data
file, or program icon) onto the appicon/appwindow, MegaD will try
to "do something" with it.  If you drag an icon onto the MegaD
appicon, then at the very least, the @{"MegaD window" link "MegaD Main Window"} will reopen.

If you drag a disk or a directory icon onto MegaD's appicon or
onto the MegaD @{"main window" link "MegaD Main Window"} (appwindow), MegaD will load that
directory into a @{"directory window" link "Directory Windows"}.

If you drag a datafile icon onto MegaD's appicon/appwindow, and
MegaD has an @{"autoboot" link "AutoBoots"} defined for that type of data file, then
MegaD will load the file into that autoboot.

You may drop up to 10 Workbench objects onto the MegaD appicon/
appwindow.  MegaD will work on each icon in sequence.


See Also:   @{" Iconify          " link "Command Iconify"} built-in command
            @{" Project " link "Menu Project"} / @{" Iconify " link "Command Iconify"} menu item
            @{" Iconify At Start " link "Prefs Defaults - Iconify At Start"} default preference

@endnode

@node "Configuring MegaD" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

Configuring MegaD:
=================

Probably the most impressive feature that MegaD has to offer is it's
configurability.  You can transform MegaD to meet your own needs.

The heart of MegaD's configurability is the @{"Preferences" link "Preferences Window"} area.


See Also:   @{" Preferences " link "Preferences Window"} main window

@endnode

