@node "Menu Windows - Open Windows" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / Open Windows:
=============================

This menu item contains two sub-menu items:


All:  This will open all windows which are currently @{"buffered" link "Buffered Directories"}
===   into memory, with one caveat.  It will still respect the
      @{"volumes per screen" link "Command VolPerScr"} and @{"windows per volume" link "Command VolPerScr"} limits.


Selected Directories:   This will open windows for all currently
====================    selected directories, volumes and devices.



See Also:   @{" Open Windows        " link "Command Open Windows"} built-in command
            @{" DirOpenWindows      " link "Command DirOpenWindows"} built-in command

@endnode

@node "Menu Windows - Close Windows" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / Close Windows:
==============================

This menu item contains two sub-menu items:


All:  This will close all currently open @{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"}.
===
   

Selected Directories:   This will close windows for all currently
====================    selected @{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"}.  The windows to
                        be closed can be selected from within other
                        @{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"}, or from the @{"list area" link "List Area"}.


See Also:   @{" Close Windows       " link "Command Close Windows"} built-in command
            @{" DirCloseWindows     " link "Command DirCloseWindows"} built-in command

@endnode

@node "Menu Windows - Use Overlap Locations" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / Use Overlap Locations:
======================================

The <Overlap Locations> command allows you to specify where directory
windows will be placed on the screen.

When selected, a new @{"directory window" link "Directory Windows"} will be placed on top of, but
offset down and to the right of it's parent @{"directory window" link "Directory Windows"}.  The
amount offset down is equal to the height of the upper window border.
The amount offset right is equal to the width of a close gadget.
Overlapping @{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"} allows for more files to be shown in
large directories.


See Also:   @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Grid Locations " link "Menu Windows - Use Grid Locations"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Set Snapshot       " link "Menu Windows - Set Snapshot"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Snapshot       " link "Menu Windows - Use Snapshot"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Limits         " link "Menu Windows - Use Limits"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Two Window Utility " link "Menu Windows - Two Window Utility"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Menu Windows - Use Grid Locations" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / Use Grid Locations:
===================================

<Use Grid Locations> tells MegaD to open new windows on an invisible
grid.  Restricting windows to a grid helps by not hiding titles
underneath other windows.  All titles are visible so a desired
directory can be found without shuffling windows around the screen.


Defining the size of the grid:
=============================

Use the @{"Windows" link "Menu Windows"} / @{"# Volumes Per Screen" link "Command VolPerScr"} and the 
@{"Windows" link "Menu Windows"} / @{"# Windows Per Volume" link "Command VolPerScr"} menu items to define the size of the grid.
MegaD uses these settings in the following manner to determine grid size:

   @{"Windows" link "Menu Windows"} / @{"# Volumes Per Screen" link "Command VolPerScr"} determines the width of each grid location.
   @{"Windows" link "Menu Windows"} / @{"# Windows Per Volume" link "Command VolPerScr"} determines the height of each grid location.

For example, if you select 3 vol per screen, and 4 win per vol, then
each grid location will be one-third the screen width, and one-fourth
the screen height.


See Also:   @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Overlap Locations " link "Menu Windows - Use Overlap Locations"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Set Snapshot          " link "Menu Windows - Set Snapshot"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Snapshot          " link "Menu Windows - Use Snapshot"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Limits            " link "Menu Windows - Use Limits"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Two Window Utility    " link "Menu Windows - Two Window Utility"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Menu Windows - Set Snapshot" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / Set Snapshot:
=============================

<Set Snapshot> records the position of open directory windows for
use with the @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{"Use Snapshot" link "Menu Windows - Use Snapshot"} window positions.


See Also:   @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Overlap Locations " link "Menu Windows - Use Overlap Locations"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Grid Locations    " link "Menu Windows - Use Grid Locations"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Snapshot          " link "Menu Windows - Use Snapshot"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Limits            " link "Menu Windows - Use Limits"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Two Window Utility    " link "Menu Windows - Two Window Utility"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Menu Windows - Use Snapshot" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / Use Snapshot:
=============================

<Use Snapshot> uses the fixed positions the @{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"} were in
when the @{"Windows" link "Menu Windows"} / @{"Set Snapshot" link "Menu Windows - Set Snapshot"} menu item was selected.  The Snapshot
positions are used on a first come first serve basis.  Unlike the
@{"Windows" link "Menu Windows"} / @{"Use Overlap Locations" link "Menu Windows - Use Overlap Locations"} and the @{"Windows" link "Menu Windows"} / @{"Use Grid Locations" link "Menu Windows - Use Grid Locations"}
options which keep volumes aligned in columns.


See Also:   @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Overlap Locations " link "Menu Windows - Use Overlap Locations"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Grid Locations    " link "Menu Windows - Use Grid Locations"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Set Snapshot          " link "Menu Windows - Set Snapshot"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Limits            " link "Menu Windows - Use Limits"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Two Window Utility    " link "Menu Windows - Two Window Utility"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Menu Windows - Use Limits" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / Use Limits:
===========================

<Use Limits> allows you to restrit the number of windows MegaD has
open at any one time.

The use of limits helps to avoid confusion when there are many large
windows overlapping each other.  It will also minimize the frequency
of low memory situations.

Use the menu items @{"Windows" link "Menu Windows"} / @{"# Volumes Per Screen" link "Command VolPerScr"} and
@{"Windows" link "Menu Windows"} / @{"# Windows Per Volume" link "Command VolPerScr"} to alter the limits, and use the
<Windows / Use Limits> menu item to toggle those limits on and off.


See Also:   @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Overlap Locations " link "Menu Windows - Use Overlap Locations"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Grid Locations    " link "Menu Windows - Use Grid Locations"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Set Snapshot          " link "Menu Windows - Set Snapshot"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Snapshot          " link "Menu Windows - Use Snapshot"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Two Window Utility    " link "Menu Windows - Two Window Utility"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Menu Windows - Two Window Utility" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / Two Window Utility:
===================================

Two Window Utility will change MegaD into the more familiar
directory program with two windows.

The main window functions are moved to the bottom of the screen.
The windows are split by button gadgets for devices.  These
device gadgets have a right and left half.  The right half
affects the right window and the left half affects the left
window.

If one window shows a directory and the opposite is empty, the
contents of the directory will be swapped to the empty window
when you select the side of a button gadget coinciding with the
non-empty window.  If both window have valid directory list in
them, and you request one of those directories in the opposite
window, both lists will be swapped to the opposite windows.

Confused???  Try <Two Window Utility>.  It's basic operation is
the same.  It's presentation is merely different.


See Also:   @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Overlap Locations " link "Menu Windows - Use Overlap Locations"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Grid Locations    " link "Menu Windows - Use Grid Locations"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Set Snapshot          " link "Menu Windows - Set Snapshot"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Snapshot          " link "Menu Windows - Use Snapshot"} menu item
            @{" Windows " link "Menu Windows"} / @{" Use Limits            " link "Menu Windows - Use Limits"} menu item

@endnode

