@node "Menu Options - Hide .INFO" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Options " link "Menu Options"} / Hide .INFO:
===========================

<Options / Hide .INFO> eliminates all icon (.info) files from directory
window displays.  Just so there's no confusion, this menu item doesn't
actually "delete" the .info files.  Rather, it hides them from view so
that your @{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"} don't get too cluttered.


See Also:   @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Select All Hide        " link "Menu Options - Select All Hide"} menu item
            @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Clear All Hide         " link "Menu Options - Clear All Hide"} menu item
            @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Hide Amiga Directories " link "Menu Options - Hide Amiga Directories"} menu item
            @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Hide C Directories     " link "Menu Options - Hide C Directories"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Menu Options - Hide Amiga Directories" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Options " link "Menu Options"} / Hide Amiga Directories:
=======================================

<Options / Hide Amiga Directories> hides all standard Amiga directories
from view in @{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"}.

Some standard Amiga directories are DEVS, FONT, and L, LIB, and S.
The Amiga automatically assigns these directories upon booting.  They
will appear on all bootable disks.  Removing them from the display helps
keep your @{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"} uncluttered.


See Also:   @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Select All Hide        " link "Menu Options - Select All Hide"} menu item
            @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Clear All Hide         " link "Menu Options - Clear All Hide"} menu item
            @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Hide .INFO             " link "Menu Options - Hide .INFO"} menu item
            @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Hide C Directories     " link "Menu Options - Hide C Directories"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Menu Options - Hide C Directories" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Options " link "Menu Options"} / Hide C Directories:
===================================

<Options / Hide C Directories> removes the Amiga C: directory
(or any directory named 'c') from the window display.  Just so
there's no confusion, this menu item doesn't actually "delete"
the C: directory(s).  Rather, it hides them from view so that
your @{"directory windows" link "Directory Windows"} don't get too cluttered.


See Also:   @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Select All Hide        " link "Menu Options - Select All Hide"} menu item
            @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Clear All Hide         " link "Menu Options - Clear All Hide"} menu item
            @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Hide .INFO             " link "Menu Options - Hide .INFO"} menu item
            @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Hide Amiga Directories " link "Menu Options - Hide Amiga Directories"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Menu Options - Keep .INFO With File" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Options " link "Menu Options"} / Keep .INFO With File:
=====================================

When you select <Options / Keep .INFO With File>, MegaD acts as follows:

   - If you select a file which has an associated .info file, MegaD will
     automatically select it's .info file too.
   
   - This DOES NOT hold true for "drag selection" (drag selection occurs
     when you select multiple files by clicking AND HOLDING the mouse
     button while you move the mouse).


When <Options / Keep .INFO With File> is NOT selected:

   - If you select a file which has an associated .info file, MegaD will
     NOT automatically select it's .info file too.  You must manually
     select it's .info file if desired.


See Also:   @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Keep Extension With File " link "Menu Options - Keep Extension With File"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Menu Options - Keep Extension With File" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Options " link "Menu Options"} / Keep Extension With File:
=========================================

When you select <Options / Keep Extension With File>, MegaD acts as
follows:

   - If you select a file which has another file containing the same
     prefix, but different file extension, MegaD will select both
     files.
   
   - This DOES NOT hold true for "drag selection" (drag selection occurs
     when you select multiple files by clicking AND HOLDING the mouse
     button while you move the mouse).
   


Example:  Lets say that your @{"directory window" link "Directory Windows"} contains the following:
          
             myfile
             myfile.c
             myfile.info
             yourfile
             yourfile.info
          
          If you select <myfile>, then MegaD will automatically select
          <myfile>, <myfile.c> and <myfile.info>.  This is because all
          three files have the same prefix (myfile) but different
          extensions.


See Also:   @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Keep .INFO With File " link "Menu Options - Keep .INFO With File"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Menu Options - Activate AutoBoot" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Options " link "Menu Options"} / Activate AutoBoot:
==================================

If <Options / Activate AutoBoot> is selected, MegaD will attempt to "do
something" whenever you double-click on a file.  If you don't select
this menu item, then all @{"autoboots" link "AutoBoots"} are disabled!!!


If the file you double-clicked on was a text file, MegaD will recognize
that, and load it into a @{"text-viewer window" link "MegaD Text-Viewer"}.  If the file is an IFF file
and you have created a picture viewer  @{"autoboot" link "AutoBoots"}, then MegaD will
automatically call that IFF viewing program to display the file.  And
so on, and so on...

For a much more indepth discussion of this subject, refer to  @{"autoboots" link "AutoBoots"}.


See Also:   @{" AutoBoots  " link "AutoBoots"} discussion
            @{" Clr ABoot  " link "Command Clr ABoot"} built-in command
            @{" Sel ABoot  " link "Command Sel ABoot"} built-in command
            @{" ABoot Add  " link "Command ABoot Add"} built-in command
            @{" ABoot Edit " link "Command ABoot Edit"} built-in command

@endnode

@node "Menu Options - Clone Copy" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Options " link "Menu Options"} / Clone Copy:
===========================

When you @{"copy" link "Command Copy"} a file to a new directory, MegaD normally does not
copy the following information:

   File Comment
   File Date

If you select <Options / Clone Copy>, then MegaD will @{"copy" link "Command Copy"} these
two items whenever a file is copied to a new directory.


See Also:   -

@endnode

@node "Menu Options - Load on disk insert" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Options " link "Menu Options"} / Load on disk insert:
====================================

When you select <Options / Load on Disk Insert>, MegaD will
automatically open a directory window for any new disk inserted
into a standard floppy drive (df0: - df3:).


See Also:   @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Free on disk remove " link "Menu Options - Free on disk remove"} menu item

@endnode

@node "Menu Options - Free on disk remove" "MegaD v3.1 - by John L. Jones"

@{" Menu Options " link "Menu Options"} / Free on disk remove:
====================================

When you select <Options / Free On Disk Remove>, MegaD will automatically
@{"unbuffer" link "Buffered Directories"} the contents of a volume which is removed from a standard floppy
drive (df0: - df3:).


See Also:   @{" Free Volumes " link "Free Volumes"} gadget
            @{" Free Volumes " link "Command Free Volumes"} built-in command
            @{" Options " link "Menu Options"} / @{" Load On Disk Insert " link "Menu Options - Load On Disk Insert"} menu item

@endnode

